From 0ff0a1b836f6bb5bb96af0be93f0fbe2378cb5fc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Max Furman <taygoth@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 1 Jun 2026 00:23:06 +0500
Subject: [PATCH 2/4] usb: typec: qcom-pmic: add PMI8998 port handler

Implement the seven tcpc_dev callbacks plus a single consolidated
type-c-change IRQ handler for PMI8998's USB Type-C controller block at
SPMI offset 0x1300.

Notable differences from the pm8150b sibling:

  - STATUS_4 (0x130e) bit positions are different: VBUS=BIT(6),
    DEBOUNCE_DONE=BIT(4), ORIENTATION=BIT(1), ATTACHED=BIT(0).
  - STATUS_1 (0x130c) reports UFP-side Rp detection (RDSTD/RD1P5/RD3P0),
    STATUS_2 (0x130d) reports DFP-side Rd detection.
  - SW_CTRL register (0x1310) power-role bits are UFP_EN=BIT(2),
    DFP_EN=BIT(1), DISABLE=BIT(0). The pm8150b ordering is reversed.
  - get_vbus() reads only the USBIN side, so it must OR with a software
    flag set by set_vbus(true) when we are SRC sourcing VBUS through our
    boost regulator.
  - Type-C change events are coalesced into a single rollup IRQ (perph
    0x13 mask 7) rather than pm8150b's separate CC-state and
    attach/detach IRQs. The ISR diffs STATUS_4 against a snapshot and
    decides whether to call tcpm_cc_change() and/or tcpm_vbus_change().
    Hardware debouncing means no cc_debounce_dwork is required.

The PDPHY block at offset 0x1700 is byte-identical to PM8150B and is
reused via the existing pm8150b_pdphy_res in qcom_pmic_typec.c.

PMI8998 leaves the chip in micro-USB mode out of reset. port_start
runs a four-write/three-delay sequence (DISABLE_CMD on, 200 ms,
clear TYPE_C_OR_U_USB_BIT, 10 ms, DISABLE_CMD off, 120 ms) to switch
the FSM into Type-C mode before enabling toggling. Without it the
chip never reports ATTACHED.

INTRPT_ENB is set to 0xff (all rollup sources) rather than the
downstream qpnp-smb2 value of 0x01 (CC-state only): downstream relies
on a separate charger driver to spot DFP-attach; the unified TCPM
path has to observe both events.

Signed-off-by: Max Furman <taygoth@gmail.com>
